english:
  title: A Letter to Military Commander Park In-seok Upon Return from Campaign
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I humbly write to you.

    Since we parted, I have been most anxious about your health and circumstances. By nature I am reckless and never bound to official rank, yet suddenly compelled and forced to serve in the military camp. Had I not found a kindred spirit in you, I would surely have cast my body into the pestilent lands and never again set foot in the capital. Fortunately, you have shown me great patronage and consideration. Morning and evening I do not leave your side—discussing letters, sharing wine, our faces bright with laughter—such pleasures are beyond words. You have sheltered my faults and supported my virtues, always concerned for my fortunes and misfortunes, striving to advance my standing. Even my own father and uncles could not love me as you do. Though my bones may someday turn to dust, this debt I shall never forget.

    Three years in the army under your protection, and I suffered barely a day's illness. When soldiers fell sick at Cloud Gate Pass, their fate was death, yet I was spared through your shield. Upon the army's return, I soon fell gravely ill. Arriving in the capital, my mind reeled as if drunk—though I reached home, I scarcely knew where I was. For months I suffered deeply before a small improvement came. My legs remain weak; I must lean upon a staff to rise. I have yet to make the rounds of courtesy calls, nor have I visited your honored son to ask if news has arrived from the south. My negligence knows no bounds.

    When first I lay ill, I looked upon my life without regret. Death held no terror for me. Yet one fear gripped my heart: that I might never again see your face, never again receive your gracious presence, never rekindle the affections of old friends. This alone kept the wish for life alive in me.

    Now my illness has eased, and counting the days of your return, few remain. Soon I shall have the fortune of your patronage once more. What cause for worry then? Recently I learned that you yourself, donning armor and grasping spear, fought the enemy and captured more than forty. When this news reached the court, I could not help but smile and clap my hands in joy. "It is just as I said!" I exclaimed. "Did I not speak thus?"

    You see, love of life and fear of death are the common sentiments of all men, as are the yearning for reward and dread of punishment. When rewards and punishments are clear and just, soldiers think thus: "If I advance and fail, I die. If I retreat, I am punished—and die. But retreat surely means death, while advance holds some chance of victory. Should I win, I not only escape death but receive reward." With such thoughts, they race forward without hesitation. How could such men not prevail? But when rewards and punishments are unclear, what incentive or warning remains? Who would abandon what they love or rush toward what they fear?

    Before, though you understood this truth, you could not wield full authority—you merely served the commanding general. Now that the great army returns and the Son of Heaven appoints you Military Commandant with complete authority, with clear rewards and punishments in your hands, how could the rebels not fall swiftly? The bandits are already doomed.

    You have heard these words from me before. Have they proven true or false? Now I may finally take some pride in what I have said. When I spoke of your imminent return, it was because I felt certain it would be so. The remaining rebels will soon be captured. Press on, press on!

    The summer heat weighs heavily, and I fear your garments may rot. I dare send this humble note to you. I only ask that you cherish yourself for the sake of the nation, attend carefully to your health and well-being, and fulfill the deep wishes and hopes I pour out toward you.

    There is more I wish to say, but I close here with two bows.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Cloud Gate Pass (雲門山): A strategic location where soldiers fell ill during military operations.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hui-eum Temple (惠陰院): A waystation or monastery where the author fell severely ill upon returning from military service.'
  - key: ''
    value: The author employs a philosophical argument about incentive structures and military discipline, drawing on classical military theory to praise his patron's leadership and predict the enemy's defeat.
  - key: ''
    value: The final advice about self-care is characteristic of Korean epistolary etiquette, where concern for the recipient's health was a conventional closing gesture.
